<author><name><![CDATA[tokumaru]]></name></author>
<updated>2013-08-13T15:08:38-07:00</updated>
<published>2013-08-13T15:08:38-07:00</published>
<id>http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=10207&amp;p=116457#p116457</id>
<link href="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=10207&amp;p=116457#p116457"/>
<title type="html"><![CDATA[Re: NES Game Project #1]]></title>

<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=10207&amp;p=116457#p116457"><![CDATA[
The interesting thing about grey in NES games is that it can be combined with different colors to create the illusion of more colors. Look at Blaster Master for example... they use the same grey to highlight the rocks and the grass, requiring only one palette to color both of them. But you have to use it with caution, since large grey areas can look quite dull.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=95">tokumaru</a> — Tue Aug 13, 2013 3:08 pm</p><hr />
]]></content>
